The paper deals with the detection of microaneurysms in fundus images using deep learning techniques, specifically convolutional neural networks. This falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new two-stage training process for the CNN, which involves optimizing the network for both feature extraction and classification. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the machine learning (cs.LG, cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of publicly available datasets for validation, indicating that it may be relevant to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with medical imaging, which suggests that it may also be relevant to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
